PART 1: The Async Typewriter Engine

    This section is responsible for the human-like typing effect in the hero section.

        JavaScript
        const sleep = (ms) => new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, ms));

    const: A keyword that declares a variable whose reference cannot be changed. It locks the definition in place.

    sleep: The name of the variable holding the function.

    = (ms) =>: This is an Arrow Function. It takes one argument, ms (milliseconds).

    new Promise: JavaScript is synchronous; it tries to execute everything instantly. A Promise forces the engine to handle a time-delayed action.

    resolve: The signal that the promise has been fulfilled.

    setTimeout(resolve, ms): A built-in browser API that waits a specific number of milliseconds (ms) before executing the resolve signal.

    JavaScript
    async function typeLine(elementId, text, speed) {
        const element = document.getElementById(elementId);
        if (!element) return;
        element.innerHTML = ""; 
        
        for (let i = 0; i < text.length; i++) {
            element.innerHTML += text.charAt(i);
            await sleep(speed);
        }
    }
    async function: Declares that this function will involve waiting (asynchronous behavior). It allows the use of the await keyword inside it.

    elementId, text, speed: The three parameters the function requires to operate (where to type, what to type, how fast).

    document.getElementById: The DOM (Document Object Model) method that searches the HTML for a specific ID.

    if (!element) return;: A defensive guardrail. If the HTML element is missing, the script aborts (return) instead of throwing 
    a fatal error that crashes the whole file.

    for (let i = 0; i < text.length; i++): A standard loop. It defines an integer i starting at 0. It runs the loop as long as i is less 
    than the total number of characters in the string, adding 1 (i++) each time.

    element.innerHTML += text.charAt(i): Targets the HTML inside the element and appends (+=) the exact character located at index i of the text string.

    await sleep(speed): Freezes the loop for the provided speed duration before typing the next letter.

PART 2: The Animation Controller (Intersection Observer)

    This engine monitors the user's scroll position and triggers CSS animations when cards enter the viewport.

    JavaScript
    const observerOptions = {
        threshold: 0.1, 
        rootMargin: "0px 0px -50px 0px" 
    };
    observerOptions: An object containing configuration data for the camera.

    threshold: 0.1: Dictates that the animation should trigger when exactly 10% of the target element becomes visible on the screen.

    rootMargin: Acts like an invisible bounding box. The -50px on the bottom means the trigger line is shifted 50 pixels up 
    from the bottom of the screen, preventing the animation from firing before the user can clearly see it.

    JavaScript
    const cardObserver = new IntersectionObserver((entries, observer) => {
        entries.forEach(entry => {
            if (entry.isIntersecting) {
                entry.target.classList.add('show');
                observer.unobserve(entry.target); 
            }
        });
    }, observerOptions);
    
    new IntersectionObserver: Invokes the browser's native, hardware-accelerated scroll API.

    entries: An array of all the HTML elements currently being monitored by this specific observer.

    entries.forEach: A loop that executes logic for every monitored element.

    entry.isIntersecting: A boolean check (True/False). Asks: "Has this specific element crossed the threshold defined in observerOptions?"

    entry.target.classList.add('show'): If true, it injects the .show class into the HTML element. The CSS file instantly reads 
    this and applies the opacity and transform physics to fade it in.

    observer.unobserve: A performance optimization. Once the card has faded in, it tells the engine to stop tracking its coordinates to save CPU processing power.

PART 3: The Tab Switcher & Slider Engine

    This logic controls the horizontal sliding panels.

    JavaScript
    function initTabSlider() {
        const tabButtons = document.querySelectorAll('.tab-btn');
        const sliderTrack = document.getElementById('slider-track');
        
        if (tabButtons.length === 0 || !sliderTrack) return;
    querySelectorAll: Unlike getElementById which finds one item, this finds every item in the HTML that has the class .tab-btn and groups 
    them into a NodeList (an array-like structure).

    The if statement provides another defensive guardrail.

    JavaScript
        tabButtons.forEach((button, index) => {
            button.addEventListener('click', function() {
                tabButtons.forEach(btn => btn.classList.remove('active'));
                this.classList.add('active');
                
                const slidePercentage = index * -25;
                sliderTrack.style.transform = `translateX(${slidePercentage}%)`;
            });
        });
    }
    
    forEach((button, index): Loops through the buttons. It tracks both the HTML element (button) and its mathematical position in the list (index: 0, 1, 2, or 3).

    addEventListener('click', ...): Attaches a click sensor to each button.

    classList.remove('active'): When a button is clicked, this loop aggressively strips the active state (the glowing dot) from all buttons to reset the UI.

    this.classList.add('active'): Applies the active state only to the specific button the user just clicked.

    index * -25: The mathematical core of the slider. Because there are 4 panels, each panel represents 25% of the track. If the user clicks
     the third button (index 2), it calculates 2 * -25 = -50.

    style.transform = translateX(...): Forces the HTML track to slide left on the X-axis by exactly that percentage, perfectly aligning 
    the correct panel with the viewport.

PART 4: Context-Aware Scroll Hint Engine

    This logic calculates viewport boundaries to show or hide the bouncing downward arrow.

    JavaScript
    function initScrollHint() {
        // ... Variable declarations and guardrails ...
        
        scrollHint.addEventListener('click', () => {
            window.scrollBy({ 
                top: window.innerHeight * 0.7, 
                behavior: 'smooth' 
            });
        });
    
    window.scrollBy: Commands the browser to scroll relative to its current position (rather than jumping to a specific element).

    window.innerHeight * 0.7: Calculates the physical height of the user's specific monitor/screen in pixels, multiplies it by 0.7, and 
    scrolls down exactly 70% of that distance.

    JavaScript
        const bottomObserver = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
            entries.forEach(entry => {
                if (entry.isIntersecting) {
                    scrollHint.classList.remove('visible');
                } else if (heroSection.getBoundingClientRect().bottom < 0) {
                    scrollHint.classList.add('visible');
                }
            });
        }, { threshold: 0 });
    
    getBoundingClientRect().bottom < 0: A mathematical UI calculation. It measures the physical bounding box of the hero section. 
    If the bottom edge of that box is less than 0 (meaning it has scrolled up and completely off the top of the screen), it reactivates the scroll hint.

